      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes standard benchmark problems (lid-driven cavity, Poiseuille flow) at expected convergence rates.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against the ASME V&V 20 benchmark suite by the vendor. Internal checks confirm second-order spatial convergence on structured meshes. Code verification is considered adequate for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) below 5% for the primary QoI (normalized hemolysis index NIH) across all five operating points, with Richardson extrapolation applied on at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (coarse 4.2 M, medium 9.8 M, fine 22.1 M cells). GCI values for NIH ranged from 3.1% to 8.7% across the five operating points. The two highest-flow operating points exceed the 5% GCI threshold. The team notes that the fine mesh captures the primary recirculation zones adequately and that overall trends in hemolysis sensitivity are consistent across refinement levels. Engineering judgment supports that the discretization uncertainty does not materially affect the worst-case identification task. The assessment is considered sufficient for the intended comparative use."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation are documented and traceable to the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "FDA generic pump experimental data (Hariharan et al.) were collected at flow rates of 2.5–7.5 L/min and rotational speeds of 2000–3500 RPM, spanning the CPB operating envelope. Test fluid (saline with RBCs) and temperature (37°C) are documented. Traceability to COU conditions is established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH values agree with experimental measurements within ±25% at all five validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values show agreement within 18% of experimental measurements across all five operating points. Systematic over-prediction at high shear rates is consistent with known SST k-omega turbulence model behavior. The acceptance criterion of ±25% is met at all points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The modeled QoI (NIH and RH index) directly corresponds to the clinical decision metric.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and the relative hemolysis index (RH = NIH_device/NIH_predicate) are the primary outputs. RH < 1 is the regulatory acceptance criterion per FDA guidance. The QoI is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of red blood cell trauma during CPB."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
